This study describes the approach that is necessary in outpatient surgery in order to carry out the operation safely. The particular procedure is discussed, and the necessity of strict postoperative management is shown. Between 1994 and 1997, the author supervised 4588 outpatient operations, of which 3020 were arthroscopic. The observed complications are listed and evaluated. Overall, outpatient surgery is well accepted by the patients. The criteria for denying a patient surgery on an outpatient basis are laid out.  
